Idaho State Department of Education
September 10 at 8:59 PM ¬∑

For Suicide Prevention Awareness Month, 2020 Idaho Teacher of the Year Stacie Lawler shares her story and encourages us to educate ourselves about suicide prevention and mental health.

Free QPR (Question, Persuade, Refer) gatekeeper training for suicide prevention is available through the SDE to educators and all members of a school's community (this includes parents, grandparents, school staff, staff at youth organizations, coaches; anyone who interacts with students at home or at school). Register here: https://form.jotform.com/200843987115156

post_text: Nice work Bridgette!
shared_text:
Idaho PTV Teachers
May 18 at 10:00 PM ¬∑

Bridgette O'Dwyer currently teaches in the Lakeland Joint School District No. 272. This week, 4th graders across Idaho get to learn from this amazing teacher on Idaho Public Television's #ClassroomIdaho!

Miss O‚ÄôDwyer is currently in her 15th year of teaching. She grew up in North Idaho and loves doing outdoor adventure sports. In this picture she is kiteboarding some perfect wind and snow. She and her boyfriend of 12 years love taking care of their feisty little black kitty named Ocho. She traveled to Thailand this fall for her fortieth birthday. In the future, she aspires to learn to kite on the water and travel to beautiful tropical places to practice and improve her skills. Miss O'Dwyer said, "I am all about Growth Mindset and self-improvement. I am so grateful for the opportunity to work with kids every day. "

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLvDo4LDXnoaD4YqdEYHDs7U_O33X6_v7h

post_text: We are so proud of the hard work that our very own Corey Friis has put in with Idaho PTV to bring remote learning to Idaho students!
shared_text:
Idaho PTV Teachers
May 19 at 9:30 PM ¬∑

6th graders from all across Idaho are lucky enough to be able to learn from Corey Friis from the Lakeland Joint School District No. 272 this week during #ClassroomIdaho on Idaho Public Television. Watch it this week on our Create channel, or the YouTube channel linked below!

Corey Friis is the math instructional coach for the Lakeland School DIstrict in Rathdrum, ID. She has made it her mission to show students that math is a part of their everyday life. She likes to incorporate math into all subject areas to make it relevant to learning. She is also passionate about character education. Showing students how they can change the world through small acts has been a personal mission throughout her career. When she isn't at work, you can find her on the sidelines of a football field, fly fishing, or hanging out with her family.

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLvDo4LDXnoaDNCrcZialcTZ1bnfJ-yf50

Idaho State Department of Education is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
May 15 at 8:45 PM ¬∑

Being mindful of our mental health is of the utmost importance as we face and adapt to the challenges presented by the COVID-19 pandemic, so for Mental Health Awareness Month (May), Idaho Teacher of the Year Stacie Lawler has a poignant and timely message to share about self-care and grace.

Please be aware of and share these helpful resources for finding help:

Idaho COVID-19 Hotline: call 888-330-3010

Idaho Suicide Prevention Hotline: call 211 or 208-398-4357

Disaster Distress Helpline: call 1-800-985-5990, or text TalkWithUs to 66746

National Suicide Prevention Lifeline: 1-800-273-8255

Find tips for maintaining mental wellness through the COVID-19 pandemic by visiting the CDC website: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/managing-stress-anxiety.html

Find a list of mental health resources organized by our department here: https://www.sde.idaho.gov/coronavirus/mental-health/COVID-19-Mental-Health-Support-Resources.pdf

Governor Brad Little TJHS Tigers Lakeland Joint School District No. 272 Idaho Department of Health and Welfare

Idaho State Department of Education
March 26 at 11:16 PM ¬∑

Feeding Site Locator: https://batchgeo.com/map/3195baf394a7f7db04ce06c69b17842f

During the current Statewide Stay-Home Order, Idaho State Department of Education approved meal sites are considered essential business and will continue to serve meals. The Stay-Home order may be viewed here: https://coronavirus.idaho.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/127/2020/03/statewide-stay-home-order_032520.pdf

Free meals for children are available at approved sites across the state. Children ages 1-18 may pick-up meals at any site, regardless of enrollment. Children must be physically present at the feeding site to receive a meal. Please contact individual sites for meal service times. To locate a feeding site near you, go to the Feeding Site Locator below. New sites are added as they are approved.

post_text: Something to consider for Spirit Lake and surrounding area families that do not currently have internet at home.
shared_text:
City of Spirit Lake
March 18 at 9:54 PM ¬∑

Suddenlink Offers Free 60-day Internet Service for Idaho Students During School Closures

For households with K-12 and/or college students who may be displaced due to school closures and who do not currently have home internet access, we are offering our Altice Advantage Internet solution for free for 60 days to any new customer household within our operating footprint.

After the first two free months expire, a customer may either cancel the service at no charge (which they can do at any time) or keep it as a regular paying Altice Advantage Internet customer for only $14.99/mo.

Please feel free to refer any residents interested in internet connectivity due to school schedule disruptions to our customer service department at (888) 633-0030.

Finally, Altice Advantage is also available, as always, at a low monthly rate to those who receive Supplemental Security Income (SSI) and are 65 years of age or older. It is also available for veterans who receive state or federal public assistance.

How an Idaho teacher earned a standing ovation during the State of the State address

Idaho State Department of Education
January 8 at 6:41 PM ¬∑

For 21 seconds, Idaho legislators honored 2020 Idaho Teacher of the Year Stacie Lawler with a standing ovation during Governor Brad Little's State of the State address! As a staunch advocate for strengthening students' mental health, Stacie has made mental health a cornerstone of her term as Teacher of the Year, and her work is supported by Superintendent Ybarra‚Äôs budget request for $1 million to develop and implement social/emotional training for all educators and district staff. Social-emotional learning is vital to helping children develop the self-awareness, problem-solving and impulse control needed to overcome challenges and thrive in school, work and community life. Lakeland Joint School District No. 272

post_text: Stacie Lawler, our amazing Idaho Teacher of the Year traveled to Boise for the State of the State Address. Check out the post below!
shared_text:
Idaho State Department of Education
January 6 at 11:55 PM ¬∑

Thank you Governor Brad Little for inviting 2020 Idaho Teacher of the Year Stacie Lawler to Boise for your State of the State Address, showcasing her wonderful accomplishments to the large audience of Idahoans listening in! Superintendent Ybarra was so pleased to have Stacie in town to meet with Governor Little, First Lady Teresa Little, Idaho State Board of Education president Debbie Critchfield, Lieutenant Governor Janice McGeachin, and Idaho legislators! Stacie was present in the State Capitol's House Chambers for Governor Little's Address, and received a standing ovation when Governor Little recognized her devotion to social-emotional learning, mental health, her students, and to the teaching profession! Stacie came all the way from Spirit Lake Idaho, where she teaches PE and Health at TJHS Tigers in the Lakeland Joint School District No. 272!

Senator Carl Crabtree

Have you heard about the Lakeland Literacy Project? This amazing program supports our community with FREE classes. This month kicks off Literacy for Little Ones. This ongoing, monthly program works with parents and their preschool-aged children to encourage early reading and participation in reading/learning activities. Statistics show that introducing babies and preschool age children to books is one of the most important factors in their later school success. We meet monthly at the District Office (15506 N Washington St, Rathdrum). Come join us as we share a fun picture book and enjoy art activities that celebrate the learning we do that day. You may attend all or as many classes as you are able! Our first class is Monday, Sept 30 12:30-1:30pm. Click below to register now!
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScjWzZBJ2Va5WH9ETG-nlZctkmYrc4wIOAcStemRWSOQqfHyg/viewform

Website:
https://sites.google.com/lakeland272.org/lakelandliteracyproject

Please join us for our first ever Summer Book Club! This is the first event organized for the Lakeland Literacy Project. Parents and their students will meet with us at Majestic Park to enjoy a great book, learn how to read with your child at home to support the acquisition of reading skills, and help our students develop a life-long love of reading. Meals will be provided for participants. We are excited to share a "wonder"ful book with you! For your convenience, we will offer two sessions each Wednesday. Feel free to choose whichever fits your schedule best. We will meet on the following Wednesdays from 11:00-12:30pm or 5:30-7:00pm at Majestic Park: 6/13, 6/20, 6/27, 7/11, 7/18, and 7/25.

Lakeland Joint School District No. 272 is accepting applications for the position of Transportation Director.
The district serves eleven schools nestled in beautiful North Idaho. Communities within the district include Rathdrum, Hauser, Spirit Lake, Athol, Twin Lakes, Garwood, and Bayview.
The Director of Transportation would oversee the operation of the school transportation program and ensure the safe and efficient transport of students. Salary will be no less than $50,000. Lakeland Joint School District is accepting applications for Substitute Custodians. Available positions will range in daily hours from approximately 3 to 5 hours (day/evenings), five days a week, during the school year. The starting wage is $10.56 per hour.

The successful applicants will have as a minimum; a high school diploma/GED; the ability to read basic operating instructions and write reports; demonstrated aptitude for successful completion of the tasks assigned.

An extensive background check (including employer recommendations, references, and a criminal history check) is required. To apply, please submit a District on-line application and resume.

School District 272 does not discriminate or deny services on the basis of age, race, religion, color, national origin, sex and/or disability. Dear Parents and Guardians,

It's time to start planning for another year of Lakeland's Invention Convention!

Invent Idaho is a students invention competition where children can showcase their creativity and innovation. Young inventors have the chance to participate in progressive levels of competition, from district level, to regional events and onto State Finals. We look forward to a fun filled year with new ideas and inspiration from all levels.

Who can Participate: All students in grades 1-12

Where does the competition take place: Garwood Elementary

Key Dates:

Please complete the online registration by December 1st, 2015.

December 5th Project Drop Off
December 6th- Project Judging
December 7th- Public Viewing
December 8th- Project Pick up

Detailed information on the competition as well as district registration can be found on the district Invent Idaho Page, http://web.lakeland272.org/invent_idaho.

http://inventidaho.com/

Feel free to contact Laura Spurway lspurway@lakeland272.org with any further questions.

post_text:
LJHS Mercury Spill Update:
At this time, any students that have been exposed to the Mercury have been evaluated and released to their parents. As you know, our #1 priority is always the safety of our students. Now that the students have been cleared, our focus shifts to the building. The Hazmat team will begin the process of testing the classroom and surrounding areas. This may take several hours, but notifications will be sent as we are updated. All bus routes, dismissal times, and after school activities remain on normal schedule.
text:
LJHS Mercury Spill Update:
At this time, any students that have been exposed to the Mercury have been evaluated and released to their parents. As you know, our #1 priority is always the safety of our students. Now that the students have been cleared, our focus shifts to the building. The Hazmat team will begin the process of testing the classroom and surrounding areas. This may take several hours, but notifications will be sent as we are updated. All bus routes, dismissal times, and after school activities remain on normal schedule.

post_text: Today, at 10:20 am, an accidental spill of approximately 1 teaspoon of Mercury occurred in an 8th grade Science Lab studying the Periodic Table at Lakeland Junior High School. Students were immediately evacuated to another classroom. Four students who were in the immediate vicinity of the spill are remaining with responders until the exposure level can be accessed. Contact has been made with all of their parents. All other students were released to their normal class schedules. The Regional Hazardous Material team, Department of Environmental Quality, Rathdrum Police, and Northern Lakes Fire District all responded and are on site. Currently, all bus routes and school dismissal remain at normal times. Further notifications will be sent as we are updated.

post_text: Thank you to our parents, staff, and students for your patience and support during the lockdown this afternoon. As you know we transitioned from PowerSchool to Skyward this summer. If you did not receive the many text alerts Dr. Meyer sent throughout the lockdown, please let your principal know. We will work with you to ensure that your contact information in Skyward is correct and that you have "opted in" for text alerts. Our IT department will be able to help us overcome individual glitches. This system is our primary mode of communication with our families and we want to ensure that you get the information you need. Thank you, again, for your patience and support today and for sharing your precious children with us! -Lisa Sexton, Assistant Superintendent

post_text: Lakeland Joint School District will be participating in a Summer Food Service program once again at Lakeland Jr. High in Rathdrum and NOW this year at SPIRIT LAKE! Lakeland Jr. High is from June 19- August 11 (closed July 3-4), Monday through Friday. Breakfast is from 8:00 a.m.-9:00 a.m. and Lunch is from 11:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m. In Spirit Lake the program will be held at the Community Center on Tuesday, Thursday, & Friday and at the City Park on Mon & Wed. Same dates and times apply as Lakeland Jr. High. For large groups please contact Tammy Cass prior at 208-691-3801.

post_text:
Full Day Kindergarten Coming to Lakeland Fall 2017!

Due in large part to the generous support of the patrons of the Lakeland Jt. School District and the passage of our Supplemental/Instructional Levy, we are thrilled to announce that beginning fall of 2017 we will offer a full-day program for every kindergartner. During the 2016-17 school year the district piloted a full-day program and targeted students who were identified as ‚Äúbelow grade level‚Äù using the Fall Idaho Reading Indicator. The students who participated in the full-day program out-performed their peers in the traditional kindergarten program. Based on the evidence from the data gathered, the decision was made to ask voters to support the full implementation of this program. We are excited about the future of public education in the Lakeland Jt. School District. Great things are coming our way! Early registration for kindergarten will be held Thursday, May 18th at each of our elementary schools from 9:00 ‚Äì 3:00. For any questions, please feel free to contact the district office at 208-687-0431.

PARENTS, TEACHERS & STUDENTS PLEASE READ:
Effective immediately, please do NOT open any emails from a district email account that includes a "shared document" (you'll see "hhhhhhhhhh" in the "To" field). We have been caught in a nation-wide spamming attack on Google. We are in the process of resolving the issue on our affected accounts but if you did click the link in your email and then log-in online then you will want to change your password.

PLEASE SHARE this post with others.

The Lakeland Joint School District is accepting applications for a full time Human Resources Director in Rathdrum, Idaho. Annual salary shall be no less than $55,000 and will be determined based on experience and education. A full Benefit Package including: employee paid medical/dental; $20,000 life insurance; retirement with PERSI; paid holidays and sick leave.
For more information please visit https://www.applitrack.com/lakeland272/onlineapp/jobpostings/view.asp?internaltransferform.Url=&internal=internal&district=&category=HUMAN+RESOURCES

post_text:
CONGRATULATIONS GARRETT!
LOREN BENOIT/Press Lakeland High School senior Garrett Mayo receives an apprenticeship from local plumbing company Sawyer Plumbing in Rathdrum. On March 7, Lakeland held a Career Day at the school, with 17 different speakers and 15 different businesses in various classrooms. A journeyman plumber can make anywhere from $25 to $30 an hour. Pictured, from left: Bob and Mary Mayo, Garrett Mayo, and Katie and Travis Sawyer. http://www.cdapress.com/article/20170427/ARTICLE/170429835
